items.name: ECGAs
items.description:
Welcome to the ECGAs! The excellence in computer graphics awards! An event run by CGC where we work with a panel of Professors in CAGD, & possibly beyond, in order to bring to you an awards event to celebrate your hard work! Submit your work for a chance to be recognized as one of the best! Submit to one of our categories: 2D Art, Animation Individual, Game Play Feature, 3D Modeling Prop, 3D Modeling Character, 3D Modeling Environment, Animation Team, Game Small Team, and finally Game Large Team. Our panel of Professors will review and judge your work to determine the best of the best! Please be sure to read the rules before submission or you may be disqualified! Possible winners will receive one of three recognitions- 1st place, 2nd place, and 3rd place! Each placement will receive one plaque for the individual or group along with certificates for all of those involved to celebrating their achievements! Make sure to include your full team member list as we only have room for 120 people! Priority will be given to submissions & there will be a student checking for names at the door. We will have a separate line for those who would like to get in, but haven't submitted. We again apologies for this, but we are limited in our capacity! However, for anyone not entering or is unable to get in due to our limited seating capacity, it's ok! We have seating for anyone there to support or wanting to watch our student submissions! We will be opening 133 & 136 to stream the ECGAs as necessary due to turn out. We- the CGC officer class are looking forward to your presence and participation! Please arrive in either formal attire (interview clothes or business casual), CSU Chico colors (maroon, black, white, silver, or grey), or show up in cosplay & support the game or animation submitted! We'd love to see some robots, cyberpunk, goblins, cowboys or whatever else we receive from our fellow students! On behalf of the officer class we hope to see you there & anticipate a great turn out! Go Wild Cats!

What is Freshmen Foundations?

As freshmen, transitioning into university life and finding time to grow in one's faith can be challenging. The goal of FRESHMEN FOUNDATIONS is to nurture the spiritual lives of freshmen: Providing unity in diversity through faith, fellowship, and fun; providing support to freshmen as they continue getting acclimated to university life; providing long-term friendships for those who struggle with the social environment of university life; providing a space for individuals to share their faith experiences; transitioning freshmen into the greater Newman community.​ Events every other Thursday @ 7pm.

items.name: Lei Day
items.description: Lei Day has been celebrated on May 1st on the Hawaiian Islands since 1928. It is a celebration of Hawaiian beauty and culture via a festival and competition for traditional lei making. While observing Lei Day, one can expect to see an abundance of lei being worn across the islands and to hear local music wherever you may go. Lei represent love, respect, and celebration, so feel free to join us in a night of lei making!

items.name: 2025 Hackathon
items.description:
On behalf of ACM-W, ACM, TPC, and UPE, we are excited to announce our first-ever collaborative Hackathon, taking place on April 25-26, 2025, from 2:00 PM Friday to 2:30 PM Saturday (~24 hours). This event is open to all students, whether you’re a first-time participant or a seasoned hackathon veteran!

Event Details:

  • Date & Time: April 25-26, 2025 | 2:00 PM Friday – 2:30 PM Saturday
  • Team Size: Teams of 3 to 5 members (minimum of 3, maximum of 5)
  • Location: On-site event on Friday and Saturday, location TBD (stay tuned for updates via Discord!)
  • Meals: Provided on-site to keep you energized and focused during the event!

How It Works:

  • Opening Ceremony: Kicks off on Friday at 2:00 PM. Here, we'll reveal this year's theme and give you the chance to collaborate and brainstorm in-person!
  • Project Development: Teams will begin working on their projects from 2:15 PM Friday. Collaboration will continue through the afternoon and morning/afternoon of Saturday until 2:30 PM. **PREVIOUS PROJECTS CANNOT BE USED. MUST BE NEW PROJECTS**
  • Final Presentations: On Saturday afternoon, teams will present their finished projects to a panel of faculty judges. The best projects will win exciting prizes! 🏆
Who Can Participate:
  • All students are welcome! Whether you’re new to hackathons or have participated before, this is your chance to challenge yourself, enhance your skills, and collaborate with peers.
  • First-time participants: This is a great opportunity to dive into the world of hackathons. Don’t worry if you’re not a coding expert—hackathons are about learning, problem-solving, and teamwork!
  • Returning participants: The format will be similar to last year’s event, with opportunities for both learning and fun!
Why You Should Join:
  • Boost Your Skills: Work on a real-world project and enhance your technical and soft skills.
  • Network & Collaborate: Meet fellow students from different disciplines and build lasting connections.
  • Resume-Boosting: Add a completed hackathon project to your portfolio—employers love seeing hands-on experience!
  • Fun & Prizes: Compete for exciting prizes and enjoy a fun, collaborative environment. 
HOW TO REGISTER:
  • Sign up via CatsConnect AND the Google Form to register yourself and your team no later than Wednesday, April 23rd, by 11:59 PM.
  • Join the 2025 Hackathon Discord. All updates regarding the event will be posted here!
  • Teams need to register individually. We have a limited capacity!
We can’t wait to see the creative solutions you’ll come up with! Ready to hack? 💻🚀
 
Questions? Join the ACM-w discord or shoot us an email: acmwchico@gmail.com.

items.name: 51st and Fight: Canada and the US in Historical Perspective
items.description: Tuesday, April 22nd at 4:30pm in Arts107 we have the privilege of having Prof. Shawn Brackett from the College of Communication and Education speak on the arising tension between the US and Canada amidst the current presidency. We hope you join us as Shawn discusses the evolving relationship between the two countries, a background of Canadian history, and what their sovereignty means in the face of political scrutiny. Shawn received his MA in Canadian History so he can help provide clarity on the situation and answer any questions you may have regarding the situation with our neighbors to the north. We hope you join us for this event, and if you have any questions please feel free to contact us!

items.name: Beyond the Walls: a panel on reentry and film screening
items.description:
This event aims to provide an intimate and powerful glimpse into the often-hidden world of formerly incarcerated individuals, particularly those who have pursued education. The event is divided into two parts: a thought-provoking panel discussion followed by a screening of an impactful film that examines the realities of life inside correctional facilities. The event shines a light on the transformative power of education and the new hope it brings to the lives impacted by the justice system. The panel is moderated by Rebound Scholars an on-campus student organization who work to create a community for justice impacted students and educate the student body about a highly stigmatized class of individuals. The panelists include formerly incarcerated individuals who have navigated the criminal justice system and now find themselves in the pursuit of higher education. They will offer a candid look at how their lives were affected by incarceration and how education has created a new path forward for them. There will be a short intermission after the panel and then the film will be screened. Food will be provided for those who attend and all are welcome. 

 

Doors open at 5:30. Panel discussion will start at 6 p.m. The movie will start at 7:30

items.name: College of Business Keynote Speaker Forum
items.description: This Event will be hosted by The Project Management Group in collaboration with the Association for Women in Business. This Event is open to ALL Chico State students regardless of major or concentration and is a great opportunity for students to come listen and learn from Chico State Alumni who are established industry professionals. This Forum will host speakers that will dive into the critical role of project management in achieving business success, focusing on leadership, agility, and strategic execution. Attendees will gain insights into navigating their careers, professional development, and how to achieve success. There will be a total of 2 guest speakers (1 provided by the PMG and 1 provided by AWIB) and will address common business challenges, offering practical strategies for enhancing team performance and project outcomes. Designed for executives, managers, and professionals, this forum will provide actionable takeaways to improve decision-making and operational success. Through real-world examples and industry best practices, this forum aims to empower Chico State Students to navigate the complex work enviroment and achieve sustainable growth in today’s competitive business environment.

items.name: English Graduate Student Council Symposium
items.description:
The English Graduate Student Council welcomes and invites you to join us for an evening of scholastic discussion and food. Student presenters will be sharing creative projects from a range of their academic coursework including: creative writing in poetry, fiction, and nonfiction as well as literature reviews, rhetorical analysis, teaching portfolios, and more. 

The event starts at 5pm in ARTS 150 with our Keynote Speaker, Dr. Ayde Enriquez-Loya. After, guests can enjoy food and refreshments and then we invite everyone to join us in ARTS 105, 106, and 107 from 6pm-7pm, with a second panel of presenters starting in the same rooms from 7pm-8pm.

*The EGSC Symposium is a scholastic forum where students can present their creative manuscripts, research, art, or writing in the fields of creative writing, literature, rhetoric, and composition. The EGSC Symposium is a dynamic, creative event that facilitates scholarly discourse and is helpful for students who seek to further their education after Chico by adding to their professional resume

items.name: Cinderella's Closet
items.description:
The California Teacher's Association - Aspiring Educators Chico Chapter, Chico Marketplace, and National Charity League have partnered once again for the 19th Annual Cinderella’s Closet prom wear giveaway for local high school students. The event will be held at Chico Marketplace on Friday and Saturday, March 29-30th from 11 am to 1 pm at Chico Marketplace (in front of the American Eagle)!

 

The goal of this event is to outfit local students with formal wear and accessories free of charge. Formal wear donations can be dropped off at the Chico Marketplace, the California Teachers Association (CTA) office, Tehama Hall, or Meriam Library. Volunteers are also welcome!

Please join us at the event and assist some very deserving students as they piece together the prom outfit of their dreams! 

 

Please be aware that dressing rooms are limited so please come in athletic/leisure wear to try on dresses/suits outside of the dressing rooms!

 

We will have a DJ, snacks, and coupon cards for Chico Marketplace outlets! 

 

For any questions/concerns please reach out to us at chicoscta@gmail.com

Hope to see you all there! <3 :)

items.name: CoolCat Closet Pop-Up
items.description: The Anthropological Society and SFAC present our ongoing pop-up event for the CoolCat Closet. This pop-up will be part of This Way To Resilience, a dynamic and interactive event focused on building resilience in the face of climate-change threats. This will be a FREE CLOTHING CLOSET for students to take from as needed. We will gladly be accepting donations from students, staff, and faculty at the time of this and each following event and are currently working to open donation bins across campus. We look forward to serving all students and hope to see you there! ☆

items.name: IEEE Micro Mouse Project
items.description: This project consists of building a robotic mouse capable of navigating a maze autonomously. The robot must remember its starting position, navigate through the maze, find the center of the maze, and return back to its home location in the fastest time possible. Interested in PCB design, firmware, and circuits? Come learn more about the project in our next meeting! We are currently looking for new members to continue the tradition of building new Micro Mouse platforms and enhancing our existing robot for new features. We welcome new, transfer, and current students to join us to learn more about the Micro Mouse project.

items.name: AS Election Endorsement Panel
items.description:
🗳️ AS Election Endorsement Panel — Your Voice. Your Vote. Your Future.

Join us for the AS Election Endorsement Panel, an exciting and impactful evening where you’ll hear directly from the candidates running to represent YOU in the Associated Students (AS) government at Chico State!

📅 Date: Thursday, March 27th
🕔 Time: 5:00 PM to 8:00 PM
📍 Location: BMU 314/316
🍪 Light refreshments provided

Hosted by the Student Coalition for Responsible Government (SCRG) — a dynamic alliance made up of Chico State Pride, the Council of Graduate Students (COGS), the MPA Professional Association (MPAPA), and a growing network of student organizations and individuals who care deeply about electing strong, principled leaders to government at all levels.

🎤 Candidates will answer questions from our three host organizations, with a chance for public Q&A if time permits.
✅ Chico State Pride and COGS will be issuing endorsements.
📜 MPAPA will be certifying candidates for public service, recognizing their readiness to lead with integrity.

This is your chance to get informed, get inspired, and get involved. Whether you're a first-time voter or a seasoned student leader, your presence and participation are essential to shaping a better student government — and a better future.

Don’t sit this one out — show up, speak up, and be part of the process. Democracy starts here.

Let’s elect the best to represent the rest.
